{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569304"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:26:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:26:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22061"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22061"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.06,0.51,0.05,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15022"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107327"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15022"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22061"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89791"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"39287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39288"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39289"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45003"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107327"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic concerned about his risk of developing cancer. He is otherwise well and has no symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His father was diagnosed with colorectal cancer at the age of 54 years, his mother was diagnosed with colorectal cancer at age 58 years, his paternal grandmother was diagnosed with colorectal cancer at age 62 years, and his paternal uncle was diagnosed with colorectal cancer at age 65 years. Genetic testing has excluded Lynch syndrome. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate colorectal cancer screening regimen for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Five-yearly colonoscopy starting now","Biennial faecal occult blood testing starting at age 45","Five-yearly colonoscopy starting at age 44","Five-yearly colonoscopy starting at age 50","Five-yearly colonoscopy starting at age 40"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is at high risk (Category 3) of developing colorectal cancer due to having two first-degree relatives (father and mother) and two second-degree relatives (paternal grandmother and paternal uncle) diagnosed with colorectal cancer. Lynch syndrome has been excluded through genetic testing. This places him at significantly increased risk compared to the general population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate screening regimen for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Efive-yearly colonoscopy starting at age 40\u003C/strong\u003E. For high-risk individuals with excluded Lynch syndrome, colonoscopy screening should begin at 10 years before the age at which the youngest first-degree relative was diagnosed or at age 40, whichever comes first. In this case, the earliest diagnosis was at age 54, so screening would start at age 40 rather than age 44.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFive-yearly colonoscopy starting now\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as the patient is only 18 years old, which is too early to begin screening even in high-risk individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiennial faecal occult blood testing starting at age 45\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended screening regimen for average-risk individuals, not those at high risk like this patient. High-risk individuals require colonoscopy rather than faecal occult blood testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFive-yearly colonoscopy starting at age 44\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for moderate-risk individuals but not for high-risk individuals, who should start at age 40.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFive-yearly colonoscopy starting at age 50\u003C/strong\u003E would be too late for this high-risk patient and is more appropriate for moderate-risk individuals when the earliest diagnosis in the family is after age 60.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent colorectal cancer risk categories based on family history and screening recommendations are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 1 - similar risk as the general population\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with no family history of colorectal cancer OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne 1st-degree relative with CRC \u226560 years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: FOBT should be completed every 2 years from 45 years old as per usual screening protocol. Colonoscopy is generally not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 2 - moderately increased risk\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with one 1st-degree relative CRC diagnosed \u003C60 years OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age or one 1st-degree and one or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed at any age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: Colonoscopy should be offered 5 yearly starting at 10 years younger than the earliest diagnosis of CRC in a 1st-degree relative, or age 50 (whichever is earliest), to age 74 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 3 - high risk\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic with two 1st-degree and one 2nd-degree relative with colorectal cancer, with at least one diagnosed before 50 years old OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives and two or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed with CRC at any age OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThree or more 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: refer to the familial cancer clinic for genetic assessment before a screening decision is made if Lynch syndrome has not been excluded. If Lynch syndrome is excluded, colonoscopy should be offered every 5 years starting at 10 years younger than the earliest age of diagnosis of colorectal cancer in a first-degree relative or age 40 years (whichever is earlier), to age 74 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELow dose aspirin has been found to reduce the risk of developing colorectal cancer and may be considered from age 45-70 as primary prevention, particularly in higher risk groups.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Individuals with two first-degree relatives and two or more second-degree relatives with colorectal cancer are at high risk and should begin colonoscopy screening at age 40 or 10 years younger than the earliest diagnosis, whichever comes first.","High-risk individuals with excluded Lynch syndrome require colonoscopy every five years.","Referral to a familial cancer service is appropriate for high-risk individuals to exclude hereditary cancer syndromes before determining screening protocols."],"references":["RACGP. Guidance for preventative activities in general practice: colorectal cancer. 2024. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/cancer/colorectal-cancer","Cancer Council Australia. Clinical practice guidelines for the prevention, early detection and management of colorectal cancer: Risk and screening based on family history. 2024. Available at: https://app.magicapp.org/#/guideline/jz5DdE"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89791"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22061"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89791"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-27T22:37:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-27T22:44:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15022"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107327"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updat